│ 0}. This narrowing is introduced during the first transformation point in     │
│ BoUpSLP::ShuffleInstructionBuilder::gather via BoUpSLP::gather's              │
│ CreateInsertElement, which performs Builder.CreateIntCast to the target       │
│ element type (ScalarTy) computed earlier. ScalarTy was reduced by MinBWs to   │
│ i16 for the gather, causing lossy truncation of i32 values like 65535 to i16  │
│ (-1).\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe root cause is applying MinBWs narrowing │
│ to the element type used by createBuildVector for gather nodes. When a gather │
│ collects integer scalars of different bitwidths (e.g., i32 values coming from │
│ zext/sext chains), choosing a smaller ScalarTy (from MinBWs) causes           │
│ CreateInsertElement to insert truncating casts, changing values and breaking  │
│ compares. Specifically, narrowing from i32 65535 to i16 changes the signed    │
│ interpretation in subsequent icmp slt, leading to the observed wrong          │
│ result.\n\nThe code path:\n- vectorizeTree computes ScalarTy, possibly        │
│ narrowed via MinBWs.\n- For E->isGather(), it calls createBuildVector(E,      │
│ ScalarTy, ...), and later CreateInsertElement casts incoming scalars to this  │
│ ScalarTy, truncating wider integers.\n\nFor compares, vectorizer already      │
│ avoids getValueType for CmpInst. However, the problematic gather here is not  │
│ the compare itself but the gather of operands and related casts, still        │
│ affected by MinBWs.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Points(s):\nWe should not apply       │
│ MinBWs narrowing to ScalarTy for gather nodes. Use the natural (non-narrowed) │
│ scalar type for createBuildVector so that the vector element type is at least │
│ as wide as the widest gathered scalar. This prevents lossy truncation inside  │
│ CreateInsertElement and preserves original semantics.\n\nEdit: In             │
│ BoUpSLP::vectorizeTree, move MinBWs-based ScalarTy adjustment after handling  │
│ the E->isGather() case, or conditionally skip MinBWs if E->isGather().        │
│ Concretely, compute ScalarTy from the original scalar V (using getValueType   │
│ for non-Cmp), and before applying MinBWs, if E->isGather(), directly call     │
│ createBuildVector with the unmodified ScalarTy.\n\nSuggested patch            │
│ (conceptual diff at lines 15050-15069):\n- Compute ScalarTy from V as         │
│ today.\n- Do not apply MinBWs to ScalarTy when E->isGather().\n- Only apply   │
│ MinBWs for non-gather nodes (the complex vectorized operations where the      │
│ element type is consistently derived from operands and costs).\n\nThis        │
│ ensures the build vector creation will use a sufficiently wide element type,  │
│ avoiding truncation in CreateInsertElement and maintaining correctness of     │
│ icmp semantics.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy skipping MinBWs narrowing for gather    │
│ nodes when selecting ScalarTy for createBuildVector, we prevent the           │
│ vectorizer from building vectors with a too-small element type. This avoids   │
│ the unsafe truncation of i32 constants (like 65535) to i16 (-1), thereby      │
│ preserving the original comparison semantics and fixing the miscompile        │
│ evidenced by Alive2. The change is localized to vectorizeTree's handling of   │
│ gathers and does not affect other vectorization cases where MinBWs is         │
│ beneficial."})                                                                │
