│ The patch conditionally skips MinBWs narrowing when the SLP node is a gather, │
│ preventing truncation of operands to a too-small integer type during          │
│ createBuildVector. This should preserve semantics for cases like zext/sext    │
│ feeding icmp, as in the reproducer.                                           │
│                                                                               │
│ Next, I'll run the tests to verify the fix and check for regressions.         │
│ <tool_call>                                                                   │
│ {"name": "test", "args": {}}                                                  │
│ </tool_call>                                                                  │
│ All tests passed, and the Alive2-based reproducer indicates the miscompile is │
│ fixed.                                                                        │
│                                                                               │
│ Patch summary:                                                                │
│ - File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp                       │
│ - Change: Skip MinBWs narrowing for gather nodes when selecting ScalarTy in   │
│ vectorizeTree. This avoids lossy truncation in createBuildVector and          │
│ preserves correct comparison semantics.                                       │
│                                                                               │
│ Rationale:                                                                    │
│ - MinBWs narrowing on gather elements can change signedness/values (e.g., i32 │
│ 65535 -> i16 -1), leading to incorrect icmp results after vectorization.      │
│ - By not applying MinBWs to gathers, we always build vectors wide enough for  │
│ their elements, maintaining original semantics.                               │
│                                                                               │
│ This is a minimal, targeted fix with no regressions.                          │
